But companies that have been riding the work from and stay at home trend, such as Zoom, Teladoc and Slack, were all tumbling Monday morning.

Message: From May 8 to June 22, about half of Americans told Axios/Ipsos pollsters that they wore masks at all times when leaving home. Middle Atlantic residents (led by New York) say they’re wearing masks at a significantly greater rate than the majority of the US. Of the over 750 Mid-Atlantic respondents, 64% say they are always wearing masks when they go out. In contrast, 33.5% of people in Alabama, Kentucky, Mississippi and Tennessee say they do. Message: Stocks are continuing their post-Election Day rally — despite the fact that it is still not yet clear who won the presidential race. Link Text: CNN Business
Description: Stocks are continuing their post-Election Day rally -- despite the fact that it is still not yet clear who won the presidential race. Investors appear to be betting though that Joe Biden will ultimately be declared the victor and the Republicans will hold on to control of the Senate. That could eventually lead to more Covid-19 related stimulus -- albeit a so-called "skinny deal" -- but the prospects for a divided government may allay fears that a so-called blue wave would usher in more regulations on tech and financial services as well as a rolling back of Trump tax cuts. In corporate news, mobile chip giant Qualcomm is surging after reporting strong earnings and sales and solid guidance. Qualcomm is expected to be one of the biggest winners of the rollout of more 5G phones and networks.

Message: Stocks are soaring Monday as investors cheered more promising news about a potential Covid-19 vaccine. Biotech Moderna announced that its coronavirus vaccine had a 94.5% efficacy rate in its latest trial, even better than the 90% effectiveness rate that Pfizer and its partner BioNTech announced last week. Shares of Moderna surged nearly 15%. The Dow and S&P 500 are flirting with record highs on the news and the Dow may even top the 30,000 level for the first time.
Link Text: CNN Business
Description: Stocks are soaring Monday as investors cheered more promising news about a potential Covid-19 vaccine. Biotech Moderna announced that its coronavirus vaccine had a 94.5% efficacy rate in its latest trial, even better than the 90% effectiveness rate that Pfizer and its partner BioNTech announced last week. Shares of Moderna surged nearly 15%. The Dow and S&P 500 are flirting with record highs on the news and the Dow may even top the 30,000 level for the first time. But investors are once again shunning big tech stocks and companies that were work from home winners. The Nasdaq is edging slightly lower and shares of Zoom, Peloton, Netflix and Clorox are all down in early trading as well.

Description: Stocks are set to kick off December in rally mode. Futures are pointing to a broadly higher open Tuesday. The Dow just wrapped up its best month in 33 years while the S&P 500 and Nasdaq are flirting with new record highs. Renewed optimism about the possibility that multiple Covid-19 vaccines could soon be available helped lift the mood on Wall Street. In corporate news, Tesla shares were heading higher after Standard & Poor's announced that it would add the stock to the S&P 500 in one fell swoop later this month. Shares of Zoom Video were lower, despite reporting strong earnings and sales and a healthy outlook. Zoom shares have been one of the market's biggest winners of 2020 as the pandemic has fueled demand for its software.

Futures are pointing to a mixed open Monday -- the last day of November. The Dow and S&P 500 are slightly lower and the Nasdaq is edging a bit higher. But the Dow is still on track for its best monthly gain in 33 years. Optimism about a Covid-19 vaccine continues to fuel Wall Street's record run. Biotech Moderna announced positive trial results for its coronavirus vaccine Monday and said it will seek FDA emergency approval, news that sent its shares soaring more than 10%. And there's a mammoth merger in the financial services world. Index provider S&P Global is buying data company IHS Markit for $44 billion. That's the biggest merger of 2020.
Link Text: Opening Bell

Message: Futures are pointing to a flat open Friday, closing out another tumultuous week on Wall Street. Stocks were headed for a bigger drop earlier in the morning but pared their losses after the United States government reported that 701,000 jobs were lost in March -- the worst month since 2009 -- and that the unemployment rate spiked to 4.4% from 3.5% in February. Job losses are likely to escalate further in the coming months as businesses shut down due to the Covid-19 pandemic. The government said that a big portion of the March job losses came from the food services industry.
Link Text: CNN Business

Message: "Both of the vaccines... are what's called a prime-boost," says Dr. Anthony Fauci of the Moderna and Pfizer Covid-19 vaccines. "One injection, followed in four weeks by another injection, 28 days. So what you have is... some degree of immunity a couple weeks after the first dose... After the second dose, you get optimal immunity anywhere from 7 to 10 days after the second dose."

Message: “It’s hard to tell if it’s because of racism or if it’s just the pandemic, but we are still down 50%.” When the coronavirus pandemic hit, Cam Voung’s Chinese restaurant, Canton House, not only saw a dramatic drop in business, but it was also the target of vandals who broke his windows. Now Asian Americans are still facing the economic consequences of Covid-19 along with the racism and xenophobia that has spread with the virus. The Asian American unemployment rate, once the lowest, is now one of the highest. CNN goes to Atlanta, where Asian American businesses are still struggling eight months into the coronavirus pandemic.
As the NBA's plans to create a "bubble" isolation zone amid the pandemic took shape, the organization also grappled with how to confront a national reckoning on race

Message: There is still a sense of unease on Wall Street Thursday. Futures are pointing to a slightly lower open on the heels of Wednesday's stock slide. Worries about a second wave of Covid-19 cases and more potential state and city lockdowns are outweighing hopes about coronavirus vaccines. The latest jobless claims numbers did not help matters. 742,000 people filed for unemployment benefits last week, the first weekly increase in a month. Description: Futures are pointing to a higher open Monday following a three day weekend for investors. Optimism about the economic and market rebound in China offset continued worries about the increase in Covid-19 cases in many American states. The tech heavy Nasdaq index is on track to extend its record setting run after closing at a new all-time high Thursday. In corporate news, shares of Uber are surging in early trading after the company announced it was buying Uber Eats rival Postmates for $2.65 billion. Message: Go There visits Colombia, which surpassed 1 million Covid-19 cases over the weekend and now holds the third-highest case tally in Latin America after Brazil and Argentina. We follow CNN’s Stefano Pozzebon as he speaks to local workers concerned about a second potential shutdown.

Message: Stocks are pointing to a flat open Tuesday as investors start to get ready for the holidays and wait for more news about the latest Covid-19 variant. Message: Stocks are heading lower at the open Thursday as investors digest a fresh batch of new economic data and pause after the S&P 500 just enjoyed its best 50-day rally in history. Message: Go There heads to Iran, where fighting Covid-19 has been extremely challenging for doctors. Message: Stocks are soaring Monday as investors cheered more promising news about a potential Covid-19 vaccine. Biotech Moderna announced that its coronavirus vaccine had a 94.5% efficacy rate in its latest trial, even better than the 90% effectiveness rate that Pfizer and its partner BioNTech announced last week. Shares of Moderna surged nearly 15%. The Dow and S&P 500 are flirting with record highs on the news and the Dow may even top the 30,000 level for the first time.
Link Text: CNN Business
Description: Stocks are soaring Monday as investors cheered more promising news about a potential Covid-19 vaccine. Biotech Moderna announced that its coronavirus vaccine had a 94.5% efficacy rate in its latest trial, even better than the 90% effectiveness rate that Pfizer and its partner BioNTech announced last week. Shares of Moderna surged nearly 15%. The Dow and S&P 500 are flirting with record highs on the news and the Dow may even top the 30,000 level for the first time. But investors are once again shunning big tech stocks and companies that were work from home winners. The Nasdaq is edging slightly lower and shares of Zoom, Peloton, Netflix and Clorox are all down in early trading as well.

Message: Stocks are looking to edge up ever so slightly Thursday -- one day after the S&P 500 finished at a record high. But all eyes are on the job market and economy. Another 712,000 Americans filed for unemployment benefits last week. While that's lower than a week ago and less than what economists were expecting, it still is an elevated level. The report comes one day before the government is set to report the November jobs figures. Economists are predicting a healthy gain in jobs but that the unemployment rate remained at 6.9% -- as many Americans remain out of work due to the Covid-19 pandemic. In corporate news, shares of supermarket giant Kroger fell in early trading after the company reported earnings that topped forecasts but sales that didn't meet expectations. The revenue miss could be a sign that the coronavirus-induced grocery shopping boom is coming to an end.
Link Text: Opening Bell

Message: Futures are pointing to a flat open Wednesday after Federal Reserve chairman Jerome Powell said in a speech that there are "significant downside risks" for the economy as a result of the Covid-19 pandemic -- despite the massive stimulus from the Fed as well as Congress to try and help consumers and businesses that have been impacted the most by the outbreak. Description: Stocks are pointing to a mixed open following another volatile week for the markets. Renewed US-China trade tensions, concerns about Hong Kong protests and lingering worries about Covid-19 are weighing on investor sentiment Friday morning. In corporate news, shares of Chinese e-commerce giant Alibaba were down in early trading despite reporting earnings and revenue that topped forecasts. Alibaba's CFO said the company is keeping a close eye on a potential US crackdown on shares of Chinese companies that are listed on American exchanges.

Message: Futures are slightly higher Wednesday morning as Wall Street kicks off a new month and the start of the second half of the year. Stocks were initially headed for a drop at the opening bell. But the market rebounded from its lows following positive clinical trial news from Big Pharma giant Pfizer and Germany's BioNTech regarding a potential Covid-19 vaccine. Payroll processor ADP also said that 2.37 million private sector jobs were added in June and reported a revised gain in jobs for May. The news comes before the government's jobs report, which will be released on Thursday as the market is closed for the July 4 holiday on Friday.
Link Text: CNN Business

Stocks were initially headed for a drop at the opening bell. But the market rebounded from its lows following positive clinical trial news from Big Pharma giant Pfizer and Germany's BioNTech regarding a potential Covid-19 vaccine. Payroll processor ADP also said that 2.37 million private sector jobs were added in June and reported a revised gain in jobs for May. The news comes before the government's jobs report, which will be released on Thursday as the market is closed for the July 4 holiday on Friday. In corporate news, Beyond Meat was surging after announcing a partnership in China with Alibaba. And FedEx is soaring after reporting strong earnings.

Message: The rally is set to continue on Wall Street Wednesday, with stocks pointing to a higher open as investors will pay close attention to what Federal Reserve chairman Jerome Powell has to say about the economy and interest rates later today. Wall Street is also waiting for the debut of cloud software firm Snowflake, a buzzy unicorn startup that has the backing of Salesforce and Warren Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway.
Link Text: CNN Business
Description: The rally is set to continue on Wall Street Wednesday, with stocks pointing to a higher open as investors will pay close attention to what Federal Reserve chairman Jerome Powell has to say about the economy and interest rates later today. Wall Street is also waiting for the debut of cloud software firm Snowflake, a buzzy unicorn startup that has the backing of Salesforce and Warren Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway. And FedEx is set to soar after reporting strong sales and earnings late Tuesday. The company is benefiting from strong e-commerce shipments in the midst of the Covid-19 pandemic.

Message: US stocks inched up at the opening bell in New York, but it's a rather quiet day on Wall Street. With the second-quarter earnings season not properly starting until next week, and little data on the economic calendar, stocks are lacking an obvious catalyst today. In recent sessions, a quiet news day has meant that investors worried about rising coronavirus infections across America.
Link Text: CNN Business

Message: Stocks are looking to rebound Wednesday, as Tesla and hard-hit tech stocks lead the charge. Drug giant AstraZeneca is slipping a bit after disclosing that is pausing a trial for a Covid-19 vaccine. Tiffany shares are set to plunge about 10% after luxury goods giant LVMH said it was no longer planning to buy the retailer.

Description: Stocks are looking to rebound Wednesday, as Tesla and hard hit tech stocks lead the charge. Drug giant AstraZeneca is slipping a bit after disclosing that is pausing a trial for a Covid-19 vaccine. Tiffany shares are set to plunge about 10% after luxury goods giant LVMH said it was no longer planning to buy the retailer. And workplace collaboration software developer Slack is tumbling after announcing weaker than expected billings growth and more concessions for customers struggling during the coronavirus pandemic.

Message: National Institutes of Health Director Dr. Francis Collins says he expects the UK Covid-19 variant is already in the US. “We don't have the kind of really rigorous surveillance system that would help us right now to find out what are the new variants that are circulating in the United States. … Ours is going to get beefed up now.” https://cnn.it/3hbORcy:=:https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/21/uk/coronavirus-variant-uk-intl/index.html?utm_medium=social&utm_source=fbCNN&utm_content=2020-12-23T14:20:52

Message: Go There heads to Florida, which now has 1 million cases as Covid-19 infections surge again nationwide. CNN’s Rosa Flores reports from a coronavirus testing site in Miami, and speaks to people in line as they wait to get tested after the Thanksgiving holiday

Dr. Sanjay Gupta debunks some misconceptions about Covid-19. Here are the facts: - Masks work. - Covid-19 affects people of all ages. - You can be infected by symptomatic and asymptomatic people. - There is no data to prove that everyone can get vaccines by this November. https://cnn.it/2HpOAoB:=:https://www.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-pandemic-09-24-20-intl/index.html?utm_medium=social&utm_source=fbCNN&utm_content=2020-09-24T12:37:03

Message: New York Governor Andrew Cuomo and Dr. Ala Stanford of the Black Doctors Covid-19 Consortium join Anderson Cooper and Dr. Sanjay Gupta for a new CNN Global Town Hall - Coronavirus: Facts and Fears. Tonight at 8 p.m. ET

Washington Nationals Manager Dave Martinez, who had a heart procedure last year, says his "level of concern went from about an 8 to a 12" after a number of Miami Marlins players and coaches tested positive for Covid-19 as MLB begins its postponed season.
Link Text: Major League Baseball season start overshadowed by Covid-19

Message: Go There heads to the UK as it begins rolling out the initial doses of a coronavirus vaccine. Manufactured by Pfizer/BioNTech and reported to have a 95% efficacy rate, the nation’s frontline health workers and individuals over the age of 80 are among the first to receive one of two doses. CNN’s Max Foster reports from a vaccination center in Cardiff.
Link Text: Inside a UK Covid-19 vaccination center as historic rollout gets underway

Message: Go There explores what flying as a transatlantic passenger in the age of Covid-19 feels like. Last week, a United Airlines flight from Newark landed at Heathrow Airport as the first in a four-week trial by the airline in which passengers and crew are tested before boarding – offering them reassurance that at least at the time of takeoff, no one had the virus. We follow CNN’s Richard Quest, who was a passenger on that flight and filmed a video diary of his experience.
Sandra Lindsay, an ICU nurse from New York who was among the first Americans to receive the Covid-19 vaccine, says she is not experiencing any "side effects at all."
Link Text: NY ICU nurse among first to get the Covid-19 vaccine says she's had "no side effects"

Message: College students, we want to know how you're handling the risk of getting Covid-19 while going back to school. Are you quarantined in your dorm room? What's your campus like? Do you feel safe? Share the details with us in the form and we may reach out to feature you in an upcoming story.
Link Text: Attending a US college or university on campus? Share your story

Message: Go There visits Santa HQ, a new app that allows for video chats with Santa Claus. With meet-and-greets around the world canceled due to Covid-19, the app's creators have come with innovative solutions so that children from around the world can still meet Santa ahead of Christmas. CNN’s Anna Stewart reports from London.

“I think we all need to acknowledge that on Jan. 21, things are going to be bad. It's going to be dark,” incoming CDC Director Dr. Rochelle Walensky says. She said she will promote more testing, vaccine distribution and health equity as a path forward. The new Covid-19 variant shows “we need to be limiting our mobility, period,” Wallensky adds. https://cnn.it/3hbORcy:=:https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/21/uk/coronavirus-variant-uk-intl/index.html?utm_medium=social&utm_source=fbCNN&utm_content=2020-12-23T14:20:52
Link Text: How the incoming CDC director says she plans to tackle to Covid-19 pandemic

Message: Go There heads to India as tens of thousands of farmers have swarmed outside New Delhi in cold temperatures to protest new agricultural laws they say could destroy their livelihoods. Additional protests have even been held across the globe in solidarity. But New Delhi is a Covid-19 hotspot, and the dense, maskless demonstrations could cause another spike in coronavirus cases, putting further strain on an already overwhelmed health care system. CNN’s Vedika Sud reports.
Link Text: Farmers gather to protest agricultural laws in India amid cold and Covid-19

Message: The Dow and S&P 500 are expected to rise slightly at the open but tech stocks should surge on Friday. The Nasdaq is pointing to a solid gain following blockbuster earnings reports Thursday night from Apple, Amazon, Facebook and Google owner Alphabet. Investors also may be encouraged by a government report Friday that showed a second straight monthly pop in consumer spending -- despite the Covid-19 pandemic.
Link Text: CNN Business
Description: The Dow and S&P 500 are expected to rise slightly at the open but tech stocks should surge on Friday. The Nasdaq is pointing to a solid gain following blockbuster earnings reports Thursday night from Apple, Amazon, Facebook and Google owner Alphabet. Investors also may be encouraged by a government report Friday that showed a second straight monthly pop in consumer spending -- despite the Covid-19 pandemic. But oil giants Exxon and Chevron are both set to drop after each company reported a wider than expected loss as energy demand and prices have plunged during the coronavirus outbreak.
